Threat Hunting > [T3]: Endpoint Hunting for Credential Dumping

Credential dumping is the process of extracting sensitive information, such as usernames and passwords, from a compromised system. This information can then be used to gain unauthorized access to other systems within the network. In this lesson, we will focus on hunting for credential dumping using Mimikatz as an example.

In this lesson, we will cover:

  • Methods attackers use for credential dumping
  • Mimikatz overview
  • Detecting Mimikatz activity in your network

 

Methods Attackers Use for Credential Dumping

Attackers can use various methods for credential dumping, including:

  • Memory dumping: Dumping the memory of a running process to extract sensitive information, such as passwords stored in plain text or hashed form.
  • Registry dumping: Extracting sensitive information, such as passwords, from the Windows registry.
  • File system dumping: Searching the file system of a compromised system for files that contain sensitive information, such as password hashes or configuration files.

Mimikatz Overview

Mimikatz is a well-known tool used for credential dumping, specifically for extracting Windows credentials. It can extract credentials from the memory of running processes, including the Local Security Authority Subsystem Service (LSASS) process, which stores passwords and other sensitive information in memory. By extracting this information, attackers can use it to move laterally within the network and carry out further attacks.

Detecting Mimikatz Activity in Your Network

If you have Sysmon installed on your endpoint, you can look for processes accessing LSASS. In large networks, this will require a baseline to avoid false positives. Here's how to do it:

  1. Search for Event ID 10 in Sysmon logs, which corresponds to the ProcessAccess event.
  2. Tune your search filter to look only for processes accessing LSASS by adding winlog.event_data.TargetImage: *\\lsass.exe to your query.

 

By filtering the results this way, you can identify potential Mimikatz activity and investigate further.

 

This concludes our lesson on hunting for credential dumping using Mimikatz as an example. Remember to implement security controls that monitor for and prevent the execution of malicious tools, enforce strong password policies, and regularly review and rotate credentials to mitigate the risks associated with credential dumping.
